\cb2 o truly understand computer networks, you need to ask and answer three questions: What is the problem? What are the possible solutions? What do these solutions look like when they are implemented?\cb1 \
\
\cb5 This book is divided into three major parts covering data transport, the control plane, and specific design (or rather technology) situations.\cb1 \
\
\cb2 Within each of these parts, there are sets of chapters that begin by asking a basic question: what is the problem? Describing the problem set in a meaningful way will often involve a good bit more theory work, so these chapters may not, at first, seem to be very practical.\cb1 \
